In .NET 10, MAUI adopted Android's **edge-to-edge** display model. `AdjustResize` is deprecated at the OS level (API 30+) and no longer shrinks your layout. The replacement is reacting to **IME window insets**.

### Recommended approach

**1. In your `AndroidManifest.xml`, keep (or set) soft input mode to `adjustResize`** — it still triggers inset callbacks even though it no longer resizes the window itself:

```xml
<activity android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" ... />
```

**2. Listen to IME insets in platform code and push the padding into your page.** Create a helper in `Platforms/Android/`:

```csharp
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

public static class KeyboardInsetHelper
{
    public static void Attach(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Page page)
    {
        page.HandlerChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (page.Handler?.PlatformView is Android.Views.View nativeView)
            {
                ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(nativeView, new InsetListener(page));
            }
        };
    }

    private class InsetListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        private readonly Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Page _page;
        public InsetListener(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Page page) => _page = page;

        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var density = v.Context!.Resources!.DisplayMetrics!.Density;
            // Push bottom padding so your input bar rises above the keyboard
            _page.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom / density);
            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Use it in your chat page:**

```csharp
public ChatPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
#if ANDROID
    KeyboardInsetHelper.Attach(this);
#endif
}
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 (old model) | .NET 10 (edge-to-edge) |
|---|---|
| `AdjustResize` shrinks the window | Window stays full-screen; IME insets tell you how much is covered |
| Layout auto-resizes | You apply `Padding`/`Margin` in response to inset callbacks |

### Tips
- **`KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`** (enabled by default) auto-scrolls *focused* `Entry`/`Editor` into view — but it doesn't push a bottom-anchored bar up, so the inset listener above is still needed for chat UIs.
- If you want an animated transition, use `ViewCompat.SetWindowInsetsAnimationCallback` instead for frame-by-frame keyboard tracking.
